{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":25507,"record_hash":"sha256:4bd25f25a6af19b79225f29703f27c154374d4624843c742576820353cd4a90f","timestamp":"2026-05-11T09:59:04.682Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yes, the `but-agentlog` changes look good to me.\n\nThe important bit is the dedupe change: it now reads the session-scoped `:record-hashes` set instead of loading/parsing the whole `:transcript` list. That is the right direction for large sessions and hook-style repeated captures. The actual transcript append and hash-set update are now paired through `MetaEdit`, so the thing that must stay in sync is handled together.\n\nThe code is still pretty small:\n- one read of existing hashes\n- retain new records\n- build transcript entries plus hashes\n- apply both edits together\n\nThe tests also cover the behavior I’d want protected: idempotency, duplicate records in one capture, growing transcript append, readback, redaction, and association behavior.\n\nThe caveats are acceptable POC tradeoffs:\n- Session/source metadata is written before the transcript batch, so the whole capture is not one giant transaction. Fixing that would expand the GitMeta batch API, and I would not do that right now.\n- If someone has old local POC data with a transcript list but no `record-hashes` set, this version won’t migrate it. Since this was not deployed, I’d avoid adding scar-tissue migration code.\n\nSo from a code-shape perspective: yes, good enough to commit. The only separate blocker is dependency packaging: `but-agentlog` still points at the local GitMeta path, which needs to become a published Git SHA before the GitButler commit.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T09:59:04.682Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}